This is a known breaking change. In .NET 10, MAUI enables **edge-to-edge** display by default on Android, which makes `adjustResize` ineffective since the window already extends behind the keyboard.

### Quick fix — `adjustPan`

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, set the soft input mode to pan:

```csharp
[Activity(WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustPan, ...)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

This scrolls the focused input into view but **doesn't resize** the page layout.

---

### Recommended fix — respond to keyboard insets

For a chat UI where you want the entire input bar and message list to shift/resize, handle the IME (keyboard) insets explicitly:

**1. In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:**

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Compatibility.Platform.Android;

[Activity(WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustNothing, ...)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Listen for keyboard (IME) inset changes
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
            Window!.DecorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
    }

    class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
            Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use whichever is taller — keyboard or nav bar
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

**2. Your XAML chat layout (unchanged from .NET 9):**

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" Command="{Binding SendCommand}" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

---

### Why this works

| .NET 9 | .NET 10 (edge-to-edge) |
|---|---|
| `adjustResize` shrinks the window | Window extends behind keyboard |
| System handled layout shift | You consume IME insets to add padding |

The insets listener fires whenever the keyboard opens/closes and adjusts the bottom padding of the root view accordingly, pushing your input bar up above the keyboard.

**Tip:** If you also target iOS, no changes are needed — iOS MAUI already handles keyboard avoidance via `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` by default.
